            <p class="pitch">Have you ever wanted to bring someone from <i>the outside</i> into a Slack conversation <b>without</b> inviting them to join your team, where they would have access to <b>every</b> channel?</p>
            <p class="solution"><span class="white">Our solution:</span> a web service that creates a temporary chat window to allow users outside <b>any</b> Slack channel to communicate within that channel only.</p>
            <div class="center">
                <a href="https://slack.com/oauth/authorize?&client_id=162439617488.163840164215&scope=commands,channels:history,channels:read,channels:write,chat:write:bot,chat:write:user,files:read,files:write:user,groups:history,groups:read,groups:write,im:history,im:write,links:read,links:write,team:read,users:read">
                  <button class="slack">Add to Slack</button>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p class="instruc">Setting up SlackPortal is simple. Just click the button to log in to your Slack account and choose a team.</p>
            <p class="instruc">Once you install it, you will be able to open a portal in your channel with the command <code>/portalopen</code>.</p>
            <p class="instruc">A URL will be generated that you can share with whoever you'd like to invite to participate in your channel.</p>
            <p class="instruc">To close the portal, use command <code>/portalclose</code>. Once a portal is closed, it cannot be reopened with the same URL.</p>
            <p class="instruc">Other commands include <code>/portalmute</code>, which temporarily blocks the portal from receiving messages from Slack,</p> <p class="instruc"><code>/portalunmute</code>, which allows message flow between Slack and the portal to resume, <p class="instruc"><code>/portalinfo</code>, which provides info' about a portal's current status, users and URL, and of course</p> <p class="instruc"><code>/portalhelp</code>, which lists all available commands.</p>
